# 10. Lookup merges

This is a critical section, because this is where RE/source values are converted into Business Central values.

---

## 10.1 Fund lookup merge

## Code

```m
#"Merged Queries" = Table.NestedJoin(#"Inserted Text Range", {"Gf_Fnds_1_01_Fn_Fund_category"}, #"Fund-PQ", {"RE Data Export Name"}, "Fund-PQ", JoinKind.LeftOuter),
#"Expanded Fund-PQ" = Table.ExpandTableColumn(#"Merged Queries", "Fund-PQ", {"BC Fund"}, {"Fund-PQ.BC Fund"}),
#"Renamed Columns2" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Removed Columns6",{{"Fund-PQ.BC Fund", "Fund Code"}})
```

## What it means

This maps the RE fund category to the BC fund code.

### Join rule

- source key: `Gf_Fnds_1_01_Fn_Fund_category`
- lookup key: `Fund-PQ[RE Data Export Name]`

### Output

`BC Fund` from the lookup becomes **`Fund Code`** in the journal.

### Risk

Possible mismatch causes:

- source values don’t exactly match lookup values
- lookup table has duplicate keys
- missing fund categories produce null `Fund Code`

---

## 10. 2 Year code logic

## Code

```m
#"Inserted Text Range1" = Table.AddColumn(#"Renamed Columns2", "Text Range", each Text.Middle([Gf_Apls_1_01_Appeal_ID], 6, 2), type text),
#"Added Conditional Column" = Table.AddColumn(#"Inserted Text Range1", "Year Code", each if [Text Range] = "00" then "NA" else [Text Range], type text)
```

## What it means

This extracts a 2-character year code from the appeal ID.

If the extracted value is `"00"`, it gets replaced with `"NA"`.

### Business meaning

This suggests year information is embedded in the appeal ID.

### Risk

Again, this depends entirely on the appeal ID always following the same positional pattern.

---

## 10. 3 Document type

```m
#"Added Custom" = Table.AddColumn(#"Removed Columns7", "Document Type", each "PAYMENT")
```

This hardcodes **`Document Type = "PAYMENT"`** for all rows at this stage.

That means all original rows are treated as payment lines before balancing logic later duplicates the journal.

---

## 10. 4 Department lookup

## Code

```m
#"Merged Queries1" = Table.NestedJoin(#"Added Custom", {"Gf_Apls_1_01_ApAtrCat_2_01_Description"}, #"DEP-PQ", {"RE data export name"}, "DEP-PQ", JoinKind.LeftOuter),
#"Expanded DEP-PQ" = Table.ExpandTableColumn(#"Merged Queries1", "DEP-PQ", {"BC Department Code"}, {"DEP-PQ.BC Department Code"}),
#"Renamed Columns3" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Expanded DEP-PQ",{{"DEP-PQ.BC Department Code", "Department Code"}})
```

## What it means

This maps a RE appeal attribute field to the BC department code.

### Output

The lookup value becomes **`Department Code`**.

### Risk

This join is especially important because if department mapping fails, journals may either reject in BC or post with incomplete dimensions.

---

## 10. 5 VAT / destination lookup used as Account No.

## Code

```m
#"Merged Queries2" = Table.NestedJoin(#"Renamed Columns3", {"Gf_Gift_subtype"}, #"VAT-PQ", {"Gift Subtype"}, "VAT-PQ", JoinKind.LeftOuter),
#"Expanded VAT-PQ" = Table.ExpandTableColumn(#"Merged Queries2", "VAT-PQ", {"BC Destination Code"}, {"VAT-PQ.BC Destination Code"}),
#"Renamed Columns4" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Expanded VAT-PQ",{{"VAT-PQ.BC Destination Code", "Account No."}})
```

## What it means

This uses gift subtype to look up a value called **`BC Destination Code`**, and then stores that in **`Account No.`**.

### Important observation

Although the lookup is named VAT-related, the result is being used as the **account number**.
So in practice this lookup is defining which GL account the original line should post to.

### Risk

This is a key place where nulls or wrong mapping will directly produce wrong account posting.

