# 11. Build BC accounting fields

---

## Balancing account placeholders

```m
#"Added Custom1" = Table.AddColumn(#"Removed Columns", "Bal. Account No.", each "null"),
#"Added Custom2" = Table.AddColumn(#"Added Custom1", "Balance Account Type", each "G/L ACCOUNT"),
#"Renamed Columns5" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Added Custom2",{{"Balance Account Type", "Bal. Account Type"}}),
#"Added Custom3" = Table.AddColumn(#"Renamed Columns5", "Account Type", each "G/L ACCOUNT")
```

## What it means

The query sets up standard BC journal columns:

- `Bal. Account No.`
- `Bal. Account Type`
- `Account Type`

At this stage:

- `Account Type` is set to `G/L ACCOUNT`
- `Bal. Account Type` is also initially `G/L ACCOUNT`
- `Bal. Account No.` is filled with the literal text `"null"`

### Important technical note

This is **not the same as true null**.
The text string `"null"` is a text value, not a blank.

Later in the script, you correctly convert these balancing fields to true nulls.
That later null cleanup is important because many importers treat the text `"null"` as invalid data.

---

## Description field

```m
#"Inserted Merged Column" = Table.AddColumn(#"Added Custom3", "Merged", each Text.Combine({[Gf_AttrCat_2_01_Description], " - ", Text.From([#"Document No."], "en-GB")}), type text),
#"Renamed Columns6" = Table.RenameColumns(#"Inserted Merged Column",{{"Merged", "Description"}})
```

## What it means

This builds the journal description as:

```text
[AttrCat2 Description] - [Document No.]
```

### Example

```text
"Daily Banking - 123456"
```

This description is later enhanced further for the balancing rows.

---

## Major Appeal Code

